        <svcproc svcproctype="replace" graphiccount="3">
            <title>Service Procedure</title>
            <specpara>
                <warning>
                    <para>To avoid property damage, personal injury, or death, park the vehicle on a flat level surface,
                        set the parking brake, turn the engine off, and chock the wheels.
                    </para>
                </warning>
            </specpara>
            <specpara>
                <warning>
                    <para>To avoid personal injury or death allow the engine cooling system to cool sufficiently before
                        performing this service procedure.
                    </para>
                </warning>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Use Figure 1 to identify the deaeration hose, heater return hose, and the recirculation
                    seal.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f059131" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../afcfigures/g059131.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="352px"
                         scalefitheight="328px"/>
                <caption>Figure 1. Hose and Seal Locations</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. Recirculation Seal</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. Heater Return Hose</callout1>
                    <callout1>3. Deaeration Hose</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install 3.5 inch conduit over the deaeration hose as shown in Figure 2 and secure with
                    one (1) cable lock strap.
                    <emph type="bold">NOTE:</emph>
                    Before securing the conduit, make sure the conduit is installed through the hole in the
                    recirculation seal and the conduit is of equal length on both sides of the recirculation seal.
                    Tighten the cable strap lock just enough to prevent the conduit from moving out of position.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f059132" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../afcfigures/g059132.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="352px"
                         scalefitheight="208px"/>
                <caption>Figure 2. Install Conduit onto Deaeration Hose</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. 3.5 Inch Conduit</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. Hole in the Recirculation Seal</callout1>
                    <callout1>3. Deaeration Hose</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install 10 inch conduit over the heater return hose as shown in Figure 3 and secure with
                    one (1) cable lock strap.
                    <emph type="bold">NOTE:</emph>
                    Before securing the conduit, make sure the conduit is installed through the hole in the
                    recirculation seal and the conduit is of equal length on both sides of the recirculation seal.
                    Tighten the cable strap lock just enough to prevent the conduit from moving out of position.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f059133" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../afcfigures/g059133.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="352px"
                         scalefitheight="208px"/>
                <caption>Figure 3. Install Conduit onto Heater Return Hose</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. 10 Inch Conduit Over the Heater Return Hose</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. Hole in the Recirculation Seal</callout1>
                    <callout1>3. Heater Return Hose</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
        </svcproc>
